nd case studies exploring a full range of press activity and press genres during this intense period of change. Along with keystone chapters on the economics of the press and periodicals, production processes, readership and distribution networks, and legal frameworks under which the press operated, the book examines a wide range of areas from religious, literary, political and medical press genres to analyses of overseas and émigré press and emerging developments in children’s and women’s press."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aBritish newspapersxHistoryy19th century. 0aBritish periodicalsxHistoryy19th century. 0aIrish newspapersxHistoryy19th century. 0aIrish periodicalsxHistoryy19th century. 0aPresszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPresszIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeals, M. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonea, Amelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBromley, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalder, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavanagh, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColligan, Colette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConboy, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper-Richet, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCsiszar, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinkelstei